A single-page browser UI for exploring the steno stroke tree emitted by `target/debug/viz-data`. It fetches `../out/viz-data.json` over HTTP (deliberately fails under `file://`) and lets a user drill from category → root stroke → child strokes, picking axis options (e.g. count/type variants) and toggling between multi-line and one-liner renderings of the current stroke's translation. There is no build step; all logic is inline `<script>`.

The JSON contract this file depends on: `DATA.categories` is `[{label, roots: [key]}]`; `DATA.nodes` maps a stroke key to a node with `children: [key]`, `terminal: bool`, optional `description`, nullable `multiLine`/`oneLiner` text, optional `oneLinerRoot` (a stroke-segment string), and an optional `axis: {kind: "count"|other, options: [{key,label}]}`. If `viz-data`'s output schema changes any of these field names or nesting, this file silently breaks (JS accesses fields directly, no schema validation). The one-liner-vs-multi-line distinction is stated (in a comment) to be per whole construct rather than per intermediate stroke, mirroring `lineflag.rs`'s semantics elsewhere in the repo — `oneLinerActive` is therefore a single global flag, not per-row state.

State is four module-level variables: `activeCategory` (index or null), `path` (explicitly-clicked keys root-to-leaf — singleton-child nodes are never recorded here), `oneLinerActive` (global bool), and `axisSelection` (Map from axis node key to chosen option key, persisting across re-renders so a choice sticks as surrounding rows change). `currentOneLinerRoot` is derived fresh each render from whichever row's resolved node carries `oneLinerRoot`.

`buildRows()` is the core traversal: starting from the active category's roots, it auto-chains through any node with exactly one child (`isSingleton`) without consuming `path`, and otherwise consumes the next entry of `path` if it's still a valid child of the current node — if not, it truncates `path` in place at that point ("self-heals" when an upstream axis change invalidates deeper choices). `resolve(key)` maps an axis node to its currently-selected option's node (never returns an axis node itself). `displayKey(key)` swaps in the one-liner-augmented first stroke segment (everything before the first `/`) when `oneLinerActive` and a `currentOneLinerRoot` exists for the reached node — this only affects display text, not the underlying key used for lookups/path building.

`render()` fully clears and rebuilds `#rows` from scratch on every state change (no diffing); it renders category chips, then root-level chips (shown unconditionally, even after a root is picked, so the choice stays changeable — same pattern used for every row's trailing children chips), then one row per entry from `buildRows()`, each with: an axis selector if that row's raw node is a multi-option axis, the one-liner/multi-line toggle (only once, at the first row where both variants exist — tracked via `toggleShown`), the preview block, and that row's own next-choice chips. `chipLabel` picks the chip text as `description`, else a derived snippet from `multiLine`/`oneLiner` (stripping a leading `"{^}"`, cutting at the first newline, truncating to 40 chars), else the raw trailing stroke segment.